****************************
******  MAKE-CPP-TPL  ******
****************************

Make-cpp-tpl is a program that converts a standard text file into C
and C++ Template files.

Let us now create an example file, using "file0001.txt" as the text
file and "tpl-file0001.c" as the C Template file, which is created by
using this command:

  gcc make-c-tpl-0001.c; ./a.out file0001.txt > tpl-file0001.c

This is what "tpl-file0001.c" should look like:


/*
####################################
#
# --- MAKE-C-TPL-0001.C ---
#
# This file named file0001.txt has been
# converted to a C Template file.
#
####################################
*/

/*
===========================================================
----- file0001.txt -----

Written in ISO/IEC 9899:2011 standard C
===========================================================
*/

/* ----- Header files ----- */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

/* ----- Typedefs, structs and unions ----- */

/* ----- Function Prototypes ----- */

/* ----- Global variables ----- */

/* ----- Program starts here ----- */
int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
  printf("####################################\n");
  printf("#\n");
  printf("# -- TEXTPATGEN GENERATED FILE --\n");
  printf("#\n");
  printf("# -- A generated text file created from:\n");
  printf("# -- tpl-decgen-001.c\n");
  printf("#\n");
  printf("# Start number: 0 ( 0x0 Hex, 00 Octal )\n");
  printf("# Finish number: 99 ( 0x63 Hex, 0143 Octal )\n");
  printf("# Numbers in a line: 10\n");
  printf("#\n");
  printf("####################################\n");
  printf("D-0000 D-0001 D-0002 D-0003 D-0004 D-0005 D-0006 D-0007 D-0008 D-0009\n");
  printf("D-0010 D-0011 D-0012 D-0013 D-0014 D-0015 D-0016 D-0017 D-0018 D-0019\n");
  printf("D-0020 D-0021 D-0022 D-0023 D-0024 D-0025 D-0026 D-0027 D-0028 D-0029\n");
  printf("D-0030 D-0031 D-0032 D-0033 D-0034 D-0035 D-0036 D-0037 D-0038 D-0039\n");
  printf("D-0040 D-0041 D-0042 D-0043 D-0044 D-0045 D-0046 D-0047 D-0048 D-0049\n");
  printf("D-0050 D-0051 D-0052 D-0053 D-0054 D-0055 D-0056 D-0057 D-0058 D-0059\n");
  printf("D-0060 D-0061 D-0062 D-0063 D-0064 D-0065 D-0066 D-0067 D-0068 D-0069\n");
  printf("D-0070 D-0071 D-0072 D-0073 D-0074 D-0075 D-0076 D-0077 D-0078 D-0079\n");
  printf("D-0080 D-0081 D-0082 D-0083 D-0084 D-0085 D-0086 D-0087 D-0088 D-0089\n");
  printf("D-0090 D-0091 D-0092 D-0093 D-0094 D-0095 D-0096 D-0097 D-0098 D-0099\n");
  printf("# -- End of file.\n");
  printf("\n");

  return 0;
}

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To return the text file back to its original state, simply use this command:

  gcc tpl-file0001.c; ./a.out > file0001.txt

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

In some of the C and C++ Template files, you may see that it uses "wchar_t" data type
which is very useful for Unicode support, and in other Template files, you may see
that the text is written to a named file. For example, "make-c-tpl-0002.c" will
automatically save the original file back to its original state as "file0002.txt".

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

